english:
  title: A Record of Manjusri Temple on Sacred Dwelling Mountain
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The mountain's lineage stretches far into antiquity, rooted in the long white peaks, winding more than a thousand leagues, skirting the eastern sea. Continuing southward another thousand leagues, it rises at its most majestic into what is called Hwagak Mountain. Beyond Hwagak, running south for several hundred leagues, there suddenly rises Sacred Dwelling Mountain, where stands the shrine of our nation's royal ancestor, the Sage-Boned General, the Great King Tiger-Sight. Thus the mountain received its name. Some say the illustrious Saintly Monk Uisang of Silla once dwelt here, and that the name derives from him. It is also called Nine Dragon Mountain, for this reason: The Great King Tiger-Sight and nine hunters entered the mountain to pursue beasts. As darkness fell, they took refuge in a rocky cavern. A tiger appeared at the entrance and roared terribly. The nine men said to one another, "The tiger seeks to devour us. One among us must surely meet his fate. Let us each cast our hats before the tiger—whomever's hat it seizes belongs to death." All threw their hats. The tiger seized the General's hat. The General stepped forth to fight the beast, but the tiger vanished and the cavern collapsed, trapping the nine hunters within. Thus it is called Nine Dragon Mountain.

    Within the mountain stand many temples. Yet the peaks tower high and cold, making winter habitation difficult. Below the mountainside, the terrain grows gentler. Manjusri Temple rightly occupies this favorable position. Where many valleys converge before it, the summer rains resound like thunder, shaking the very mountain. In winter, ice forms and can be broken for drinking water, easy to draw and use. Long had the temple fallen into ruin and desolation. A certain monk sought to restore it and asked me to compose this record. The work is now complete—truly admirable.

    I have long harbored the desire to wander these mountains, yet illness has constrained me. Though I wish to fulfill this ancient longing, I cannot know if Heaven will grant me further days. Should Heaven bless me with continued life, I shall take up my walking staff or ride in a carriage to roam these slopes. Among ancient trees and weathered rocks, beneath pavilions open to the wind, I shall whistle and compose verses to ease my heart. Upon thousand-fathom peaks, shaking dust from my robes, playing the bamboo flute while gazing across ten thousand leagues—would this not bring solace to this troubled spirit of mine?

    The temple halls and Buddha images, the bells and stone chimes, the daily vessels—all have been largely completed through the great generosity of one patron: the wife of Lee Sijo, Minister of State, known by the name Chogun, of Sungsan—Madam Ha of the river clans. Those who contributed are all recorded below in complete roster, compiled into one volume and permanently installed at the temple gate, that those who come after may have reference.

    In the twelfth lunar month of the year of the Blue Dragon, this record was inscribed.
  footnotes:
    - 'Hwagak Mountain: A sacred peak in traditional Korean geography, considered a major axis of the peninsula''s sacred geography.'
    - 'Uisang (義相): A renowned Buddhist monk of the Silla period, founder of the Hwaeom school of Buddhism, closely associated with mountain temples.'
    - The Nine Dragon legend reflects the ancient Korean theme of spiritual transcendence through sacrifice and the mystical power of sacred mountains.
    - Lee Saek (1328-1396) was a renowned Goryeo-era Confucian scholar and official. This personal reflection on aging and longing for mountain travel reflects both Buddhist and Daoist influences characteristic of the literati of his time.
